{{Infobox medical condition | Name = Adipomastia | Image = Gynecomastia 001.jpg | Width = 250px | Caption = A male with probable comorbid gynecomastia and pseudogynecomastia. | Field = [[Plastic surgery]] | DiseasesDB = | ICD10 = | ICD9 = | ICDO = | OMIM = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicineSubj = | eMedicineTopic = | MeshID = }}
'''Adipomastia''', or '''lipomastia''', also known colloquially as '''fatty breasts''',<ref name="LaufgrabenLaufgraben2013">{{cite book|author1=Clinical Assistant Professor Brown University Providence Rhode Island Attending Physician Hallette Center for Diabetes Providence Rhode Island Marc J Laufgraben|author2=Marc J. Laufgraben|author3=Geetha Gopalakrishnan|title=Tarascon Adult Endocrinology Pocketbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=D19wLdlnb2oC&pg=PA205|date=3 June 2013|publisher=Jones & Bartlett Publishers|isbn=978-1-4496-4857-2|pages=205–}}</ref> is a [[medical condition|condition]] defined as an excess of [[skin]] and [[adipose tissue]] in the [[breast]]s without true breast [[gland|glandular tissue]].<ref name="DennisBowen2016">{{cite book|author1=Mark Dennis|author2=William Talbot Bowen|author3=Lucy Cho|title=Mechanisms of Clinical Signs - EPub3|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2lj_DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA599|date=31 August 2016|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-7295-8561-3|pages=599–}}</ref><ref name="O'DonohueBenuto2014">{{cite book|author1=William T. O'Donohue|author2=Lorraine T. Benuto|author3=Lauren Woodward Tolle|title=Handbook of Adolescent Health Psychology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KX29BAAAQBAJ&pg=PA246|date=8 July 2014|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-1-4614-6633-8|pages=246–}}</ref> It is commonly present in men with [[obesity]], and is particularly apparent in men who have undergone massive [[weight loss]].<ref name="Hochberg2007">{{cite book|author=Z. Hochberg|title=Practical Algorithms in Pediatric Endocrinology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cliUBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA21|date=1 January 2007|publisher=Karger Medical and Scientific Publishers|isbn=978-3-8055-8220-9|pages=21–}}</ref><ref name="ThallerCohen2013">{{cite book|author1=Seth Thaller|author2=Mimis Cohen|title=Cosmetic Surgery After Massive Weight Loss|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lXXGSRjKhDIC&pg=PA133|date=28 February 2013|publisher=JP Medical Ltd|isbn=978-1-907816-28-4|pages=133–}}</ref> A related/synonymous term is '''''pseudogynecomastia'''''.<ref name="Thomas2016">{{cite book|author=Nihal Thomas|title=Clinical Atlas in Endocrinology & Diabetes: A Case-Based Compendium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d2yJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA387|date=30 April 2016|publisher=JP Medical Ltd|isbn=978-93-5152-857-9|pages=387–}}</ref> The condition is different and should be distinguished from [[gynecomastia]] ("women's breasts"), which involves true glandular [[breast development]] in a male.<ref name="Thomas2016" /> The two conditions can usually be distinguished easily by [[palpation]] to check for the presence of glandular tissue.<ref name="ThallerCohen2013" /><ref name="NieschlagBehre2013">{{cite book|author1=Eberhard Nieschlag|author2=Hermann Behre|title=Andrology: Male Reproductive Health and Dysfunction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=05fsCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA232|date=29 June 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-662-04491-9|pages=232–}}</ref> Another difference between the conditions is that [[breast pain|breast pain/tenderness]] does not occur in pseudogynecomastia.<ref name="Hochberg2007" /> Sometimes, gynecomastia and pseudogynecomastia are present together; this is related to the fact that fat tissue expresses [[aromatase]], the [[enzyme]] responsible for the [[biosynthesis|synthesis]] of [[estrogen]], and estrogen is produced to a disproportionate extent in men with excessive amounts of fat, resulting in simultaneous glandular enlargement.<ref name="Hochberg2007" /><ref name="Kappy(M.D.)2005">{{cite book|author1=Michael Steven Kappy|author2=David B. Allen (M.D.)|author3=Mitchell E. Geffner|title=Principles and Practice of Pediatric Endocrinology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JlqcQ0WhU_kC&pg=PA261|year=2005|publisher=Charles C Thomas Publisher|isbn=978-0-398-07554-5|pages=261–}}</ref>
